  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated Emergency Recovery Programme in Delta State</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The heavy rainfall in July, August and early September in 2012, coupled with the release of water from the dams on the River Gongola, River Niger and River Kaduna in Nigeria, and Lagdo dam in Cameroon, has resulted in the worst flooding in more than 40 years. To date the National Emergency Management Agency (NEMA) has registered 363 reported deaths and 2.1 million internally displaced people (IDPs). Over 7.7 million people and 33 out of the 36 states of the Federation were affected.
Reports by interagency rapid assessment teams showed that almost every community affected by the flood has suffered severe damage to livelihoods, destruction of farmlands, houses, bridges, schools and health facilities, as well as damage to the water supply, irrigation systems, and food storage and processing facilities. 
Population estimates in both Patani and Bomadi (communities affected by the flood) from the last National census stood at 154,000. The lastest flood affected up to 80% of the entire population in this location. The impact of the disaster was exacerbated by: (1) the fact that it affected mainly poor rural communities dependent on subsistence farming for their livelihoods; (2) poor pre-existing conditions of infrastructure for water and electricity supply; and (3) poor standards of buildings and equipment in the education and health sectors, of road networks and of other public/community assets.
Objective of the Project:
To ensure adequate access to integrated emergency response through provision of unconditional cash transfers, Livelihood recovery and WASH interventions to 2500 households (HHs) (17,500 vulnerable persons.) 
The project will facilitate the production of vouchers and ID cards to approve households benefiting from the UCT program in collaboration with near-by banks. Each household will get 48.28 EUR per month (for 4 months). Also, the project will identify and work with Agricultural institutions and agencies such as IITA and Agricultural Development Program (ADP) to facilitate access to farm inputs such as improved cassava cuttings and plantain suckers. The project aims to rehabilitate 6 community boreholes; carry out training on hygiene, hygiene promotion sessions focusing on 3 key hygiene practices including the distribution of water purification and storage kits to 1,400 direct beneficiaries.</narrative>
  </description>
